{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01K6C5sRd9BSfXS3Hp8vDcnZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see:\n1. `rate-api` Ingress handles `/api` on `rate.example.com` - no rate limiting annotations\n2. `rate-health` Ingress handles `/health` on `rate.example.com` - no rate limiting\n\nI need to add rate limiting annotations to the `rate-api` Ingress. The key annotations for ingress-nginx rate limiting are:\n- `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-rps`: limits requests per second\n- `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-connections`: limits connections\n\nFor 1 QPS, I'll use `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-rps: \"1\"`.\nWhen rate-limited requests are rejected, ingress-nginx returns a 503 status code by default when using the `limit-rps` directive. The burst multiplier defaults to 5, so with a 1 RPS limit, the first 5 requests would actually pass through before rate limiting takes effect. For my test sending 10 requests over 5 seconds at 2 QPS, those initial 5 requests would go through, then subsequent ones would be rate limited.\n\nI could be more aggressive by setting `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` to reduce the burst window to just 1 request, which would rate limit almost everything after the first request since they'd arrive faster than the 1-second interval allows. Actually, nginx uses a leaky bucket algorithm, not token bucket. With `rate=1r/s` and `burst=5`, the first request passes immediately, the next 5 queued requests also pass (since `nodelay` is typically enabled), and anything beyond that gets rejected. Since these test requests are spread over 5 seconds at 0.5-second intervals, the first request goes through and the burst capacity handles the rest without hitting the limit.\n\nLet me simplify and just test with the `limit-rps: \"1\"` annotation directly. The test sends 10 requests at 2 QPS while the limit is 1 QPS, so some should definitely get rate limited. The default burst multiplier in nginx-ingress will determine how many requests slip through before hitting the limit. the remaining requests get queued up. With requests arriving every 0.5 seconds, the first six pass immediately using the burst allowance, then requests seven through ten have to wait for the token bucket to refill at the 1 request-per-second rate. By around t=3.5 seconds, enough tokens have accumulated for request seven to go through, while the later ones continue waiting.\n\nLet me reconsider with a simpler approach: setting the burst multiplier to 1 gives us a burst capacity of just one extra request. At that rate with 2 QPS, the first request uses up the burst slot, the second gets rejected since only half a second has passed and the rate hasn't refilled yet, then by the one-second mark the rate replenishes and request three passes, while request four gets rejected again.\n\nThis pattern would result in roughly half the requests being rejected, which satisfies the requirement. I'll go with `limit-rps: \"1\"` and `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` and now update the rate-api ingress configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2331,"cache_read_input_tokens":28654,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2331},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9599933d-d741-4b68-8ea0-abc12ed9e85e","uuid":"75afefb5-e491-47a0-bea2-5f804d46c693","request_id":"req_011CcafE9Z55hRcX98Cqc8ZT"}
